// =============================================================================
// Appendix A: Divergence Kernel Examples (Formal)
// =============================================================================

define appendix_formal = ArxivAppendix("A", "Divergence Kernel Examples",
"*Set theory.* Let $T_\"base\"$ be the cardinal-arithmetic fragment of ZFC (ordering, addition, multiplication, exponentiation, power-set growth law). Let $T_1 = T_\"base\" union {frak(c) = aleph_1}$ and $T_2 = T_\"base\" union {frak(c) > aleph_1}$. Then:

$ Delta(T_1, T_2) = { phi in \"Sent\"(cal(L)) | phi \"depends on the value of\" frak(c) } $

The generator is the single sentence $frak(c) = aleph_1$.

*International law.* Let $T_\"base\"$ consist of Article 2(4), necessity, proportionality, and Security Council authorization. Let $T_1 = T_\"base\" union \"StrictArticle51\"$ and $T_2 = T_\"base\" union \"AnticipatoryArticle51\"$. The only structural difference is the disjunct $or \"imminent\\_attack\"(...)$ in $T_2$'s self-defense precondition. The generator is:

$ \"imminent\\_attack\"(\"target\"(a), \"attacker\"(a)) \"being satisfiable for some\" a $

*Music.* Let $T$ be the seven-axiom TonalHarmony theory. Let $T_\"Bach\" = T$ (all seven axioms enforced) and $T_\"Beethoven\" = {\"axioms 1, 2, 4, 5\"}$ (tonal cohesion only). The generators of $Delta(T_\"Bach\", T_\"Beethoven\")$ are:

$ { \"axiom 3 (triadic arpeggiation)\", \"axiom 6 (no parallel fifths)\", \"axiom 7 (harmonic rhythm)\" } $

*Chess.* Let $T$ be the fixed rules of chess. There is no theory-level divergence: $Delta(T, T) = emptyset$. Divergence appears at the proof-strategy level, where different scaffolding structures supply different intermediate lemmas to guide the SMT solver.")

